      <hedline>
        <hl1>Lebanon and Israel</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Letter from Stephen R Silberfarb (Jewish Community Relations Council of Minnesota and the Dakotas) says Israel would never have occupied a sliver of Lebanon if Lebanon had kept its border with Israel secure</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>It is indeed sad that many lives were lost and others changed because of the situation in southern Lebanon (news article, June 5). Of course, that goes for both sides of the border.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>It is indeed sad that many lives were lost and others changed because of the situation in southern Lebanon (news article, June 5). Of course, that goes for both sides of the border.</p>
        <p>Nevertheless, the bitterness felt by those in southern Lebanon suddenly ''freed'' of Israeli occupation ought not be viewed in a vacuum. Israel would not have occupied a sliver of Lebanon but for Lebanon's refusal or inability to keep its border with Israel secure.</p>
        <p>STEPHEN R. SILBERFARB  Minneapolis, June 5, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer is executive director, Jewish Community Relations Council of Minnesota and the Dakotas.</p>
      </block>
